<h1>Problem 1949 - 2024 IMO, P4 of 6, G</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 6</h2>
<p>Let \(ABC\) be a triangle with \(AB < AC < BC\). Let the incenter and incircle of triangle \(ABC\) be \(I\) and \(\omega\), respectively. Let \(X\) be the point on line \(BC\) different from \(C\) such that the line through \(X\) parallel to \(AC\) is tangent to \(\omega\). Similarly, let \(Y\) be the point on line \(BC\) different from \(B\) such that the line through \(Y\) parallel to \(AB\) is tangent to \(\omega\). Let \(AI\) intersect the circumcircle of triangle \(ABC\) at \(P \ne A\). Let \(K\) and \(L\) be the midpoints of \(AC\) and \(AB\), respectively. 
Prove that \(\angle KIL + \angle YPX = 180^{\circ}\).</p>
